  "prompt": "What is the difference between \"don't we verb\" and \" do we not verb\"?",
  "response": "The phrases \"don't we verb\" and \"do we not verb\" are both forms of negative questions in English, but they differ in terms of formality, emphasis, and usage context. Here\u2019s a breakdown of the differences:\n\n### 1. **Formality:**\n- **\"Don't we verb\"** is more informal and commonly used in casual conversation.\n- **\"Do we not verb\"** is more formal and less frequently used in everyday speech. It is often found in written English or more formal spoken contexts.\n\n### 2. **Emphasis:**\n- **\"Don't we verb\"** is straightforward and does not carry a strong emphasis on the negative aspect of the question.\n- **\"Do we not verb\"** can sound more emphatic because it places the negative element (\"not\") at the end of the phrase, making it stand out more.\n\n### 3. **Usage Context:**\n- **\"Don't we verb\"** is more versatile and can be used in a variety of contexts. For example:\n  - \"Don't we need to leave soon?\" (informal, casual)\n- **\"Do we not verb\"** might be used in contexts where the speaker wants to draw attention to the question or in more formal settings. For example:\n  - \"Do we not have a meeting at 3 PM?\" (formal, possibly rhetorical)\n\n### Examples:\n- **\"Don't we go\"**:\n  - \"Don't we go to the park every Sunday?\" (informal)\n- **\"Do we not go\"**:\n  - \"Do we not go to the park every Sunday?\" (more formal, possibly with an emphasis on the regularity of the action)\n\nIn summary, while both constructions are grammatically correct and serve to ask a negative question, \"don't we verb\" is used more commonly in informal settings, and \"do we not verb\" is more formal and can be used to add emphasis or in more structured contexts.",
